<subsubsection xml:id="subsubsec-area-of-octagons" xmlns:xi="http://www.w3.org/2001/XInclude">
    <title>Area of Octagons</title>
    <objectives component="outcomes">
        <introduction>
            <p>
            <dl>
                <li>
                    <title>Strand</title>
                    <p>
                        2.0 Measurements and Geometry
                    </p>
                </li>
                <li>
                    <title>Sub-Strand</title>
                    <p>
                        2.5 Area of Polygons
                    </p>
                </li>
                <li>
                    <title>Specific Learning Outcomes</title>
                    <p>
                        Work out the area of regular heptagon and octagon. Explore the area of polygons as used in real-life situations.
                    </p>
                </li>
                <li component="lesson-plan">
                    <title>Grade Level</title>
                    <p>
                        10
                    </p>
                </li>
                <li component="lesson-plan">
                    <title>Estimated Duration</title>
                    <p>
                        40 minutes
                    </p>
                </li>
            </dl>
            </p>
            <p component="lesson-plan">
                <p> Upon completion of this lesson, learners will be able to:
                <ol>
                    <li>
                        <p>
                            <alert>Know (Conceptual Understanding):</alert> Define properties of regular octagons, including that dividing into 8 congruent triangles with circumradius <m>R</m> and vertex angle <m>45^\circ</m> enables area calculation using <m>A = 2R^2\sqrt{2}</m>.
                        </p>
                    </li>
                    <li>
                        <p>
                            <alert>Do (Procedural Skill):</alert> Calculate the area of a regular octagon using the formula <m>A = 2R^2\sqrt{2}</m> and express answers in simplest surd form.
                        </p>
                    </li>
                    <li>
                        <p>
                            <alert>Apply (Application/Problem-Solving):</alert> Apply the octagon area formula to solve real-world problems involving octagonal structures such as pavilions, stop signs, and garden beds.
                        </p>
                    </li>
                </ol>
                </p>
            </p>
        </introduction>
    </objectives>
    <axiom component="resources">
        <!-- Link to blurb -->
        <xi:include href="../../resources-blurb-lesson.ptx" />

        <sbsgroup widths="45% 45%" margins="2% 2%">
            <sidebyside>
                <p>
                    <dataurl source="lesson_plans/measurements-and-geometry/area-of-polygons/area-of-octagons.pdf"> Lesson Plan </dataurl>
                </p>
                <p>
                    <dataurl source="lesson_plans/measurements-and-geometry/area-of-polygons/step-by-step-guide_area-of-octagons.pdf"> Step-by-Step Guide </dataurl>
                </p>
            </sidebyside>
        </sbsgroup>
    </axiom>
    <xi:include href="../../resources-materials.ptx" />

    <axiom component="lesson-plan">
        <title>Phase 1: Problem-Solving and Discovery</title>
        <p>
            <alert>Expected Time:</alert> 15 minutes
        </p>
        <p>
            <alert>Anchor Activity:</alert> Constructing and Analysing a Regular Octagon
        </p>
        <p>
            Organise students into groups of 2–3. Students draw a circle with a given radius on graph paper, mark 8 equally spaced points at <m>45^\circ</m> intervals, and connect them to form a regular octagon.
        </p>
        <p>
            <alert>Facilitation Strategy:</alert>
        </p>
        <p>
            <ul>
                <li>
                    <p>Demonstrate how to use a protractor to mark <m>45^\circ</m> intervals around the circle.</p>
                </li>
                <li>
                    <p>Guide students to draw lines from the centre to each vertex, creating 8 congruent triangles.</p>
                </li>
                <li>
                    <p>Ask: <q>What is the vertex angle for each triangle?</q> (Expected: <m>45^\circ</m>)</p>
                </li>
                <li>
                    <p>Probe: <q>Why are all 8 triangles identical?</q></p>
                </li>
            </ul>
        </p>
        <p>
            <alert>Expected Outcome:</alert> Students should discover that the area of the octagon <m>= 8 \times</m> area of one triangle.
        </p>
    </axiom>


    <p xml:id="auto_gxxksqaf"> A regular octagon is an(8-sided) polygon with eight vertices (corners) and ten edges (sides).
    </p>
    <activity xml:id="auto_88250qv0">
        <statement>
            <p>
                Constructing a Regular Octagon
            </p>
            <p>
                Working in groups of 3-5 students.
            </p>
            <p>
                <m>\textbf{Materials needed:}</m>
            </p>
            <ul>
                <li>Compass</li>
                <li>Ruler</li>
                <li>Protractor</li>
                <li>Pencil</li>
                <li>Eraser</li>
                <li>Graph paper (optional)</li>
            </ul>
            <p>
                <ol>
                    <li>
                        <p>
                            Draw a Circle
                        </p>
                        <ul>
                            <li>Use a compass to draw a circle of your desired radius.</li>
                            <li>Mark the center (O).</li>
                        </ul>
                    </li>
                    <li>
                        <p>
                            Draw the First Diameter
                        </p>
                        <ul>
                            <li>Use a ruler to draw a horizontal diameter (P0 to P5) passing through the center.</li>
                        </ul>
                    </li>
                    <li>
                        <p>
                            Divide the Circle into 8 Equal Parts
                        </p>
                        <ul>
                            <li>Use a protractor to measure angles of <m>\frac{360^\circ}{8}</m> from point P0.</li>
                            <li>Mark each 45° interval on the circle to get 8 points.</li>
                        </ul>
                    </li>
                    <li>
                        <p>
                            Connect the Points
                        </p>
                        <ul>
                            <li>Use a ruler to connect the eight points in order to form the octagon.</li>
                        </ul>
                    </li>
                </ol>
            </p>
        </statement>
    </activity>
            <p xml:id="auto_6czg2cog">
                <m>\textbf{Discussion Questions}</m>
            </p>
            <p xml:id="auto_8slk6q5x">
                <m>\textbf{Study Questions}</m>
            </p>
        <p xml:id="auto_ydkb99am">
            
        1. What is the sum of all interior angles of an octagon ?    </p>
    <p xml:id="auto_wfzbv9c5">
        2. How do we calculate the measure of one interior angle of a regular octagon?
    </p>
    <p xml:id="auto_yxpicyol">
       3. Have you ever seen octagon-shaped objects in real life?
    </p>
  
    
    <image width="50%">
    <latex-image label="regular-octagon">
        \begin{tikzpicture}[every node/.style={font=\small}]
            % Define the octagon
            \foreach \i in {0,1,...,7} {
            \coordinate (P\i) at ({360/8*\i}:2);
            }
            % Draw the octagon
            \draw (P0) -- (P1) -- (P2) -- (P3) -- (P4) -- (P5) -- (P6) -- (P7) -- cycle;
            % Label the vertices
            \foreach \i in {0,1,...,7} {
                \node[font=\small] at ({360/8*\i}:2.2) {$P_{\i}$};
            }
        \end{tikzpicture}
    </latex-image>
    </image>
    
    <insight>
        <p>
            1. Regular octagons (<m>8</m>-sided polygons with equal sides and angles) appear in many real-life contexts:
        </p>
        <p>
            Architecture: Octagonal pavilions, gazebos, towers
        </p>
        <p>
            Landscaping: Flower beds, garden features, paving patterns
        </p>
        <p>
           Traffic: Stop signs (regular octagon shape) 
        </p>
        <p>
           Sports: Octagonal boxing rings, martial arts mats 
        </p>
        <p>
            Design: Tiles, decorative patterns, building layouts
        </p>
        <p>
            <alert>Strategy: Divide into Triangles</alert> 
        </p>
        <p>
            The key strategy for finding the area of any regular polygon is to divide it into congruent triangles:
        </p>
        <p>
            Draw lines from the center to each vertex
        </p>
        <p>
            For an octagon, this creates <m>8</m> identical triangles
        </p>
        <p>
            Each triangle has two sides equal to the circumradius <m>R</m> and a vertex angle of <m>45^\circ</m>
        </p>
        <p>
            <alert>Formula for Area of One Triangle</alert>

        </p>
        <p>
            Each triangle in the octagon has:
        </p>
        <p>
            Two equal sides of length <m>R</m> (the circumradius)
        </p>
        <p>
            Vertex angle <m>\theta = 45 ^\circ</m>
        </p>
        <p>
            Using the formula for the area of a triangle with two sides and an included angle:
        </p>
        <p>
           A triangle <m>=\frac{1}{2} \times R^2 \times sin(45^\circ)</m> 
        </p>
        <p>
            Since <m>\sin(45^\circ) = \frac{\sqrt{2}}{2}</m>, we can simplify:
        </p>
        <p>
            A triangle <m>=\frac{1}{2} \times R^2 \times \frac{\sqrt{2}}{2} = \frac{R^2 \sqrt{2}}{4}</m>
        </p>
        <p>
            <alert>Formula for Area of Regular Octagon</alert>
        </p>
        <p>
            Since the octagon contains <m>8</m> identical triangles:
        </p>
        <p>
            A octagon <m>= 8 \times \frac{R^2 \sqrt{2}}{4} = 2R^2\sqrt{2}</m>
        </p>
        <p>
            Therefore, the area of a regular octagon can be expressed in terms of its circumradius <m>R</m> as:
        </p>
        <p>
            <m>A = 2R^2\sqrt{2}</m>
        </p>
        <p>
            <alert>Understanding Circumradius</alert>
        </p>
        <p>
           The circumradius R is the distance from the center of the octagon to any vertex. It is the
            radius of the circle that passes through all vertices of the octagon (the circumscribed circle). 
        </p>
        <p>
            <alert>Why This Formula Works</alert>
        </p>
        <p>
           he octagon is divided into <m>8</m> congruent triangles 
        </p>
        <p>
            Each triangle has area <m>\frac{1}{2}R^2sin(45^\circ)</m>
        </p>
        <p>
            Total area <m>=8\times(\frac{1}{2}R^2sin(45\circ)) = 4R^2sin(45\circ) = 2R^2\sqrt{2}</m>
        </p>
        <p>
            This method works for any regular polygon: divide by <m>n</m>, use angle <m>360^\circ/n</m>
        </p>
        <p>
            <alert>Scaffolding Strategies</alert>
        </p>
        <p>
            Emphasize that circumradius <m>R</m> is from center to vertex, not center to side
        </p>
        <p>
            Use visual diagrams to show the <m>8</m> triangles clearly
        </p>
        <p>
            Review <m>sin(45\circ) = \frac{\sqrt{2}}{2}</m> before calculations
        </p>
        <p>
            Connect to special angles lesson (<m>45\circ</m> is a special angle)
        </p>
        <p>
            Provide formula reference card: <m>A = 2 R^2\sqrt2</m>
        </p>

    </insight>

    <axiom component="lesson-plan">
        <title>Phase 2: Structured Teaching and Learning</title>
        <p>
            <alert>Expected Time:</alert> 10 minutes
        </p>
        <p>
            After students have explored through the anchor activity, formalize their discoveries with the key concepts in the insight section.
        </p>
        <p>
            Direct students to the key concepts in their textbooks. Walk through the content, emphasizing:
        </p>
        <p>
            <ul>
                <li>
                    <p>The strategy of dividing a regular octagon into 8 congruent triangles from the centre.</p>
                </li>
                <li>
                    <p>Each triangle has two sides of length <m>R</m> (circumradius) and a vertex angle of <m>45^\circ</m>.</p>
                </li>
                <li>
                    <p>The formula: <m>A = 2R^2\sqrt{2}</m></p>
                </li>
                <li>
                    <p>Circumradius <m>R</m> is from centre to vertex, <alert>not</alert> centre to side.</p>
                </li>
            </ul>
        </p>
        <p>
            <alert>Scaffolding Tips:</alert>
        </p>
        <p>
            <ul>
                <li>
                    <p>Review <m>\sin(45^\circ) = \frac{\sqrt{2}}{2}</m> before calculations.</p>
                </li>
                <li>
                    <p>Connect to the special angles lesson (<m>45^\circ</m> is a special angle).</p>
                </li>
                <li>
                    <p>Provide a formula reference card: <m>A = 2R^2\sqrt{2}</m></p>
                </li>
            </ul>
        </p>
    </axiom>

    <axiom component="lesson-plan">
        <title>Phase 3: Practice and Application</title>
        <p>
            <alert>Expected Time:</alert> 15 minutes
        </p>
        <p>
            Direct students to the worked examples in their textbooks. Work through the first example as a class, then allow students to attempt the remaining examples independently or in pairs.
        </p>
        <p>
            <alert>Guiding Tips:</alert>
        </p>
        <p>
            <ul>
                <li>
                    <p>Remind students to identify the circumradius <m>R</m> from the problem.</p>
                </li>
                <li>
                    <p>Ensure students express answers in simplest surd form where required.</p>
                </li>
                <li>
                    <p>Encourage students to check their work by calculating approximate decimal values.</p>
                </li>
            </ul>
        </p>
    </axiom>

        <example xml:id="auto_7t0k84m4">
        <statement>
            <p>
                A regular octagon  with O as its centre.
               If OA is 8 cm, find its area.
            </p>
                   <image>
        <latex-image label="regular-octagon-named-example">
            \begin{tikzpicture}[every node/.style={font=\small}]
                % Define heptagon properties
                \def\R{3} % Radius of heptagon
                \def\angle{360/8} % Angle between vertices for an octagon

                % Define heptagon vertices counterclockwise
                \foreach \i in {0,1,2,3,4,5,6,7} {
                    \coordinate (P\i) at (\i*\angle:\R);
                }

                % Define center
                \coordinate (O) at (0,0);

                % Draw the heptagon
                \draw (P0) -- (P1) -- (P2) -- (P3) -- (P4) -- (P5) -- (P6) -- (P7) -- cycle;

                % % Label the vertices
                % \foreach \i/\name in {0/A, 1/B, 2/C, 3/D, 4/E, 5/F, 6/G, 7/H} {
                %     \node[scale=1.1] at (P\i) {\textbf{\name}};
                % }

                % Draw dashed lines from O to A and B
                \draw[dashed] (O) -- (P0) node[midway, below left] { 8 cm};
                \draw[dashed] (O) -- (P1) node[midway,  right] {8 cm};
                 % % Label the vertices
                % \foreach \i/\name in {0/A, 1/B, 2/C, 3/D, 4/E, 5/F, 6/G, 7/H} {
                %     \node[scale=1.1] at (P\i) {\textbf{\name}};
                % }
                % Draw arc for 45° angle
                \draw (9:0.5) arc (9:50:0.5);
                \node at (20:1) {$45^\circ$}; 

                % Mark center point
                \filldraw[black] (O) circle (2pt) node[above left] {\textbf{O}};
            \end{tikzpicture}
        </latex-image>
        </image>
            </statement>
        <solution>
            <p xml:id="auto_60k67mud">
                There are 8 triangles since an octagon has 8 sides.
                Area of Triangle <m>AOB = \frac{1}{2} ab \text{sin} 45^\circ </m> 
            </p>
            <p xml:id="auto_18arfv2k">
                <md>
                    <mrow>  \amp \triangle AOB = \frac{1}{2}\times 8\times 8\, \text{sin} \, 45^\circ </mrow>
                    <mrow> \amp = \frac{1}{2}\times 64\, \text{cm}^2 \times \text{sin} \,  45^\circ</mrow>
                    <mrow> \amp = \frac{1}{2}\times 64\, \text{cm}^2 \times 0.7071 </mrow>
                    <mrow> \amp = 22.6274 \, \text{cm}^2 </mrow>
                    
                </md>
            </p>
            <p xml:id="auto_7exzxkrz">
                Therefore the total area 
                <md>
                    <mrow> \amp = 8 \times 22.6274 \, \text{cm}^2 </mrow>
                    <mrow> \amp = 181.02 \, \text{cm}^2 </mrow>
                </md>
            </p>
        </solution>
     
    </example>
    
    <example xml:id="auto_d5906h1a">
        <statement>
            <p xml:id="auto_wna7dzhx">
                The figure below represents a regular octagon with O as its centre.
                If OA is 7cm, find its area
            </p>
                       <image width="50%">
        <latex-image label="octagon-example-two">
            \begin{tikzpicture}[every node/.style={font=\small}]
                % Define heptagon properties
                \def\R{3} % Radius of heptagon
                \def\angle{360/8} % Angle between vertices for an octagon

                % Define heptagon vertices counterclockwise
                \foreach \i in {0,1,2,3,4,5,6,7} {
                    \coordinate (P\i) at (\i*\angle:\R);
                }

                % Define center
                \coordinate (O) at (0,0);

                % Draw the heptagon
                \draw (P0) -- (P1) -- (P2) -- (P3) -- (P4) -- (P5) -- (P6) -- (P7) -- cycle;

                % % Label the vertices
                % \foreach \i/\name in {0/A, 1/B, 2/C, 3/D, 4/E, 5/F, 6/G, 7/H} {
                %     \node[scale=1.1] at (P\i) {\textbf{\name}};
                % }

                % Draw dashed lines from O to A and B
                \draw[dashed] (O) -- (P4) node[midway, below left] {7cm};
                \draw[dashed] (O) -- (P3) node[midway,  right] {7 cm};
                 % % Label the vertices
                % \foreach \i/\name in {0/A, 1/B, 2/C, 3/D, 4/E, 5/F, 6/G, 7/H} {
                %     \node[scale=1.1] at (P\i) {\textbf{\name}};
                % }
                <!-- % Draw arc for 45° angle
                \draw (9:135:0.5) arc (9:180:0.5);
                \node at (20:1) {$45^\circ$}; -->

                % Mark center point
                \filldraw[black] (O) circle (2pt) node[above right] {\textbf{O}};
            \end{tikzpicture}
        </latex-image>
        </image>
        </statement>
                <solution>
            <p xml:id="auto_cel3k5sp">
                There are 8 triangles since an octagon has 8 sides and the sum of interior angles of one triangle is <m>360 ^\circ</m>.
                Area of Triangle <m>AOB = \frac{1}{2} ab \, \text{sin} \, 45^\circ </m> . 
            </p>
            <p xml:id="auto_wbbim6z9">
                The angle of <m>\triangle AOB = \frac{360}{8} = 45^\circ </m>
                <md>
                    <mrow>  \amp \triangle AOB = \frac{1}{2}\times 7\times 7 \, \, \text{ sin} \, 45^\circ </mrow>
                    <mrow> \amp = \frac{1}{2}\times 49\, \text{cm}^2 \times \text{sin}\, 45^\circ</mrow>
                    <mrow> \amp = \frac{1}{2}\times 49\, \text{cm}^2 \times 0.7071 </mrow>
                    <mrow> \amp = 17.3241 \, \text{cm}^2 </mrow>
                    
                </md>
            </p>
            <p xml:id="auto_pkizzrbe">
                Therefore the total area 
                <md>
                    <mrow> \amp = 8 \times 17.3241 \, \text{cm}^2 </mrow>
                    <mrow> \amp = 138.59\, \text{cm}^2 </mrow>
                </md>
            </p>
        </solution>
    </example>

    <axiom component="lesson-plan">
        <title>Phase 4: Assessment — Exit Ticket</title>
        <p>
            <alert>Expected Time:</alert> 5 minutes
        </p>
        <p>
            Students complete the following questions individually.
        </p>
        <p>
            <alert>Question 1:</alert> A regular octagon has a circumradius of 7 m. Calculate the area in simplest surd form.
        </p>
        <p>
            <alert>Answer:</alert> <m>A = 2R^2\sqrt{2} = 2 \times 49 \times \sqrt{2} = 98\sqrt{2} \text{ m}^2</m>
        </p>
        <p>
            <alert>Question 2:</alert> An octagonal gazebo has a circumradius of 3.5 m. Find the approximate area to one decimal place.
        </p>
        <p>
            <alert>Answer:</alert> <m>A = 2 \times (3.5)^2 \times \sqrt{2} = 24.5\sqrt{2} \approx 34.6 \text{ m}^2</m>
        </p>
        <p>
            <alert>Question 3:</alert> Explain why we divide a regular octagon into 8 triangles when calculating its area. What is the vertex angle of each triangle?
        </p>
        <p>
            <alert>Answer:</alert> We divide the octagon into 8 triangles because each triangle is congruent and has two sides equal to the circumradius with a known vertex angle. This makes calculation systematic. The vertex angle is <m>\frac{360^\circ}{8} = 45^\circ</m>.
        </p>
    </axiom>

<exercises xml:id="exercises-octagons">
    <title>Exercises</title>

    <exercise xml:id="ex-octagon-perimeter">
        <statement>
            <p>
                A regular octagon has a side length of <m>5 \text{ cm}</m>. Calculate its perimeter.
            </p>
        </statement>
        <solution>
            <p>
                Perimeter = <m>8 \times 5 = 40 \text{ cm}</m>.
            </p>
        </solution>
    </exercise>

    <exercise xml:id="ex-octagon-area-simple">
        <statement>
            <p>
                A regular octagon has a radius (distance from the center to a vertex) of <m>6 \text{ cm}</m>. Draw the octagon and calculate its area. Use <m>\text{sin } 45^\circ = 0.7071</m>.
            </p>
            <image>
                <latex-image label="octagon-area-simple-diagram">
                    \begin{tikzpicture}[every node/.style={font=\small}]
                        % Define the octagon
                        \foreach \i in {0,1,...,7} {
                            \coordinate (P\i) at ({360/8*\i}:2);
                        }
                        % Draw the octagon
                        \draw (P0) -- (P1) -- (P2) -- (P3) -- (P4) -- (P5) -- (P6) -- (P7) -- cycle;
                        % Draw radius
                        \draw[dashed] (0,0) -- (P0) node[midway, right] {6 cm};
                        % Mark center point
                        \filldraw[black] (0,0) circle (2pt) node[below] {\textbf{O}};
                    \end{tikzpicture}
                </latex-image>
            </image>
        </statement>
        <solution>
            <p>
                Area of one triangle = <m>\frac{1}{2} \times 6 \times 6 \times \text{sin } 45^\circ = 12.73 \text{ cm}^2</m>.
            </p>
            <p>
                Total area = <m>8 \times 12.73 = 101.84 \text{ cm}^2</m>.
            </p>
        </solution>
    </exercise>

    <exercise xml:id="ex-octagon-area-formula">
        <statement>
            <p>
                In the following diagram, an octagon withside length <m>s</m> has been drawn, and a square has been placed around it. By finding the area of the cut off corners, or otherwise, show that:
                <m>\text{Octagon Area} = 2(1+\sqrt{2})s^2</m>.
            </p>
            <image>
                <latex-image label="octagon-derivation-diagram">
                    \begin{tikzpicture}[scale=0.6, every node/.style={font=\small}]
                        % Outer square and inner octagon (formed by cutting corner triangles)
                        \coordinate (A) at (0,0);
                        \coordinate (B) at (4,0);
                        \coordinate (C) at (4,4);
                        \coordinate (D) at (0,4);

                        % Draw outer square
                        \draw (A) -- (B) -- (C) -- (D) -- cycle;

                        % Draw inner octagon by cutting corners at distance x from each corner
                        \draw[fill=white] (1,0) -- (3,0) -- (4,1) -- (4,3) -- (3,4) -- (1,4) -- (0,3) -- (0,1) -- cycle;

                        % Labels for lengths: octagon side s, cut-off leg x, square side L
                        \draw (1,0) -- (3,0) node[midway, below] {$s$};
                        \draw (0,0) -- (1,0) node[midway, below] {$x$};
                        \draw (0,4) -- (4,4) node[midway, above] {$L$};

                        % Corner points for clarity
                        \filldraw[black] (A) circle (1pt);
                        \filldraw[black] (B) circle (1pt);
                        \filldraw[black] (C) circle (1pt);
                        \filldraw[black] (D) circle (1pt);
                    \end{tikzpicture}
                </latex-image>
            </image>
        </statement>
        <solution>
            <p>
                Start with a square that contains the octagon: cut off four identical right isosceles triangles from the corners of a square to form the regular octagon.
            </p>
            <p>
                Let the octagon side be <m>s</m>. Each cut-off triangle is right isosceles with hypotenuse equal to the octagon side <m>s</m>, so each leg has length <m>x = \tfrac{s}{\sqrt{2}}</m>.
            </p>
            <p>
                The side length of the containing square is <m>L = s + 2x = s + 2\left(\tfrac{s}{\sqrt{2}}\right) = s(1+\sqrt{2})</m>.
            </p>
            <p>
                Area of the square is <m>L^2 = s^2(1+\sqrt{2})^2 = s^2(3+2\sqrt{2})</m>. The four removed triangles together have area
                <m>4\times \tfrac{1}{2}x^2 = 2x^2 = 2\left(\tfrac{s^2}{2}\right) = s^2</m>.
            </p>
            <p>
                Therefore the octagon area is
                <m>A = L^2 - s^2 = s^2(3+2\sqrt{2}) - s^2 = s^2(2+2\sqrt{2}) = 2(1+\sqrt{2})s^2.</m>
            </p>
        </solution>
    </exercise>

    <exercise xml:id="ex-octagon-side-from-area">
        <statement>
            <p>
                The area of a regular octagon is <m>77.25 \text{ cm}^2</m>. Using the formula <m>\text{Area} = 2(1+\sqrt{2})s^2</m>, find the side length to the nearest tenth of a centimetre.
            </p>
        </statement>
        <solution>
            <p>
                Using <m>A = 2(1+\sqrt{2})s^2</m>, solve for <m>s</m>:
                <md>
                    <mrow>s = \sqrt{\dfrac{A}{2(1+\sqrt{2})}}</mrow>
                </md>
            </p>
            <p>
                Substitute the numbers: <m>s = \sqrt{\dfrac{77.25}{2(1+1.414)}} = \sqrt{\dfrac{77.25}{4.828}} \approx \sqrt{16} = 4 \text{ cm}.</m>
            </p>
        </solution>
    </exercise>
</exercises>

    <axiom component="lesson-plan">
        <title>Differentiation</title>
        <p>
            <alert>Struggling Learners:</alert>
        </p>
        <p>
            <ul>
                <li>
                    <p>Provide pre-drawn octagons with triangles marked.</p>
                </li>
                <li>
                    <p>Use formula reference cards: <m>A = 2R^2\sqrt{2}</m></p>
                </li>
                <li>
                    <p>Review <m>\sin(45^\circ) = \frac{\sqrt{2}}{2}</m> before calculations.</p>
                </li>
                <li>
                    <p>Allow calculators for <m>\sqrt{2}</m> approximation.</p>
                </li>
                <li>
                    <p>Break into explicit steps: identify <m>R</m>, apply formula, simplify.</p>
                </li>
            </ul>
        </p>
        <p>
            <alert>On-Level Learners:</alert>
        </p>
        <p>
            <ul>
                <li>
                    <p>Complete all practice problems independently.</p>
                </li>
                <li>
                    <p>Explain the formula derivation to a peer in their own words.</p>
                </li>
                <li>
                    <p>Express answers in both surd form and decimal approximation.</p>
                </li>
            </ul>
        </p>
        <p>
            <alert>Advanced Learners:</alert>
        </p>
        <p>
            <ul>
                <li>
                    <p>Derive the formula <m>A = 2R^2\sqrt{2}</m> from first principles.</p>
                </li>
                <li>
                    <p>Extend to other regular polygons (pentagon, hexagon, decagon).</p>
                </li>
                <li>
                    <p>Compare octagon area to inscribed/circumscribed circles.</p>
                </li>
                <li>
                    <p>Explore the relationship between side length and circumradius.</p>
                </li>
                <li>
                    <p>Calculate the apothem (perpendicular distance from centre to side).</p>
                </li>
            </ul>
        </p>
        <p>
            <alert>Extension — Real-World Connections:</alert>
        </p>
        <p>
            Area of octagons is essential in architecture (pavilions, gazebos, towers), traffic engineering (stop sign design), sports (boxing rings), and construction (material estimation for octagonal structures).
        </p>
    </axiom>

